The paper deals with computational complexity in hedonic games, which are a type of game theory. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.GT (Game Theory and Economics). The paper also discusses the use of algorithms and computational methods to analyze these games, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also discusses the stability concepts of core stability, individual stability, and Nash stability, which suggests that it could belong to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Finally, the paper discusses the formalisms of additively separable games, games with W-preferences, and fractional hedonic games, which suggests that it could belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning).
